Speaker 2: You mentioned the, I guess, dynamic translations.

753
00:52:36,122 --> 00:52:37,790
Speaker 2: What are the other schools of translation?

754
00:52:37,870 --> 00:52:38,294
Speaker 2: I'm curious.

755
00:52:38,334 --> 00:52:39,990
Speaker 2: This is not a topic I know a lot about.

756
00:52:40,811 --> 00:52:41,072
Speaker 0: Right.

757
00:52:41,112 --> 00:52:41,635
Speaker 0: Okay.

758
00:52:41,796 --> 00:52:44,030
Speaker 0: I learned a lot about this on my master's course.

759
00:52:44,351 --> 00:52:50,970
Speaker 0: I did a translation studies course, and this is actually where a lot of the documentary comes from.

760
00:52:51,510 --> 00:52:55,590
Speaker 0: My, I guess, graduation thesis, you call it, dissertation.

761
00:52:55,990 --> 00:53:03,210
Speaker 0: My end-of-year dissertation was on anime translation, anime and game translation, and the two different schools.

762
00:53:03,970 --> 00:53:08,950
Speaker 0: And a lot of my quotes and things that I use in the video come directly from my dissertation.

763
00:53:09,653 --> 00:53:11,610
Speaker 1: Is there a way for us to get the dissertation?

764
00:53:13,912 --> 00:53:17,610
Speaker 0: I think it's on my DeviantArt account.

765
00:53:18,370 --> 00:53:23,170
Speaker 0: I think it's on either that or the one from the year before from my actual Japanese course.

766
00:53:23,490 --> 00:53:25,309
Speaker 0: But I'll dig it out and put it up somewhere.

767
00:53:27,072 --> 00:53:34,090
Speaker 0: But yeah, basically, it's a translation debate that's raged since Bible translation times.

768
00:53:34,770 --> 00:53:36,499
Speaker 0: And there's two schools, basically.

769
00:53:36,540 --> 00:53:38,470
Speaker 0: I mean, there's more than two, but there's two main ones.

770
00:53:38,952 --> 00:53:43,630
Speaker 0: One half thinks that the original language is so great that you need to leave it all in the original format.

771
00:53:43,870 --> 00:53:50,490
Speaker 0: And the other side says that that defeats the point of translation, and they actually want to translate it into the target language.

772
00:53:51,330 --> 00:54:00,870
Speaker 0: And so as an English translator who translates into English, I follow a school called Dynamic Equivalence that actually wants to translate anime, manga and games into English.

773
00:54:01,630 --> 00:54:07,589
Speaker 0: And some good examples of dynamic equivalents are games like Phoenix Wright, which I'm sure you're aware of.

774
00:54:08,595 --> 00:54:10,290
Speaker 0: You must have played Phoenix Wright.

775
00:54:12,037 --> 00:54:12,965
Speaker 1: I own all four.

776
00:54:13,005 --> 00:54:13,510
Speaker 1: I beat them all.

777
00:54:16,554 --> 00:54:19,950
Speaker 0: All the jokes and all the puns have just been expertly localized.

778
00:54:20,850 --> 00:54:23,061
Speaker 0: Or games like Snatcher on the Sega CD.

779
00:54:23,081 --> 00:54:24,990
Speaker 0: Do you know about Snatcher?

780
00:54:25,634 --> 00:54:26,164
Speaker 1: I know of it.

781
00:54:28,490 --> 00:54:34,550
Speaker 0: Well, you know Jeremy Blaustein, the translating god who translated Metal Gear Solid?

782
00:54:34,976 --> 00:54:35,350
Speaker 1: I do now.

783
00:54:36,571 --> 00:54:39,639
Speaker 0: Yeah, well, Metal Gear Solid, the script on.

784
00:54:39,679 --> 00:54:44,130
Speaker 0: that is probably one of the greatest translation scripts I've ever read in my entire life.

785
00:54:44,810 --> 00:54:48,769
Speaker 0: But he started out doing Konami games like Snatcher, translating them.

786
00:54:49,951 --> 00:54:52,750
Speaker 0: And basically that's just Dynamic Equivalence.

787
00:54:53,330 --> 00:54:59,850
Speaker 0: Like, you won't find a single honorific or a single cultural note in Snatcher or in Metal Gear.

788
00:54:59,950 --> 00:55:07,390
Speaker 0: Basically, if you didn't know that it was Japanese, you'd think that Metal Gear had been written by Tom Clancy or someone.

789
00:55:08,470 --> 00:55:17,870
Speaker 0: And that's kind of the point of Dynamic Equivalence, that you are creating a translation which someone reads and it sounds completely natural to them.

790
00:55:18,390 --> 00:55:24,809
Speaker 0: And so not once in their head are they taken out of the experience of watching the show by thinking, "Ooh, that sounds a bit

791
00:55:24,849 --> 00:55:25,130
Speaker 0: weird.".

792
00:55:25,330 --> 00:55:35,010
Speaker 0: It just sounds... And I'm not, for one second, saying that you should change names and change Yakumo in 3x3 eyes to Brad Spangler or something.

793
00:55:36,054 --> 00:55:36,906
Speaker 0: You should never do that.

794
00:55:38,273 --> 00:55:46,010
Speaker 0: But yeah, Dynamic Equivalence is just... Well, another example is Dark Horse's early manga translations that I was talking about.

795
00:55:46,691 --> 00:55:51,270
Speaker 0: They convert all the honorifics in their Japanese terms to English and they just do an incredible top class job.

796
00:55:52,071 --> 00:56:04,250
Speaker 0: And probably the translations of Appleseed and Dominion and Ghost in the Shell were just some of the greatest examples of a seamless read which doesn't lose any of the original plot story or character names.

797
00:56:05,050 --> 00:56:07,189
Speaker 0: And again, no honorifics, nothing like that.

798
00:56:07,833 --> 00:56:11,430
Speaker 1: So these fansubbers, what they're doing is following the other school.

799
00:56:12,410 --> 00:56:17,822
Speaker 1: And you say in your video that all the professional companies are in your school.

800
00:56:17,842 --> 00:56:21,510
Speaker 1: Are there any professionals who have the other idea about it?

801
00:56:23,093 --> 00:56:25,449
Speaker 0: Well, the other school is called Formal Equivalence.

802
00:56:26,451 --> 00:56:29,770
Speaker 0: And again, it all comes from Bible translation mainly.

803
00:56:30,232 --> 00:56:34,029
Speaker 0: And it believes that if you change any of the source text, you lose the meaning and you ruin it.

804
00:56:34,530 --> 00:56:42,329
Speaker 0: Which is why fansubbers leave in all the honorifics and put in the Japanese name order and produce incredible lines like the famous "Inawashishiro

805
00:56:42,369 --> 00:56:42,730
Speaker 0: Kamehamehasi.".

806
00:56:43,992 --> 00:56:45,140
Speaker 0: I can't even read it.

