811
00:56:56,693 --> 00:56:58,030
Speaker 1: I didn't understand that at all.

812
00:56:59,015 --> 00:57:02,270
Speaker 0: I thought probably that I should repeat that about five times in the video.

813
00:57:04,690 --> 00:57:07,630
Speaker 0: But yeah, unfortunately, that's the problem.

814
00:57:08,010 --> 00:57:19,330
Speaker 0: A lot of DVD companies now are moving towards the Formal Equivalence because they've seen, I guess, that that's what fansubbers and people who watch anime mainly watch fansubs.

815
00:57:19,731 --> 00:57:21,048
Speaker 0: I think it's fair to say.

816
00:57:22,892 --> 00:57:23,736
Speaker 0: That's what they want.

817
00:57:23,857 --> 00:57:25,043
Speaker 0: They want Formal Equivalence.

818
00:57:25,083 --> 00:57:26,470
Speaker 0: They want everything in Japanese.

819
00:57:26,550 --> 00:57:33,410
Speaker 1: I mean, outside of the anime translation world, say the people who translate French films to English.

820
00:57:34,250 --> 00:57:39,870
Speaker 1: There's a lot of translating of Hollywood movies into all sorts of other languages.

821
00:57:40,210 --> 00:57:43,140
Speaker 1: Japanese, French, German, Italian.

822
00:57:43,481 --> 00:57:46,250
Speaker 1: Are those people also using Dynamic Equivalence?

